{"id":"2202.07084","submitter":"Sandra Palau","authors":"Airam Blancas and Sandra Palau","title":"Coalescent process point process of a branching process in varying\n  environment","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.PR","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  Consider a doubly infinite branching tree in varying environment. The\ngenealogy of the current generation backwards in time is uniquely determined by\nthe coalescent point process $(A_i, i\\geq 1)$, where $A_i$ is the coalescent\ntime between individuals $i$ and $i+1$. In general, this process is not\nMarkovian. In constant environment, Lambert and Popovic (2013) proposed a\nMarkov process of point measures $(B_i, i\\geq 1)$ to reconstruct the coalescent\npoint process. We present a counterexample where we show that their process has\nnot the Markov property.\n  We define a vector valued Markov process with the minimal amount of\ninformation to reconstruct the genealogy of the standing population. We\nhighlight that this process is the Markovian correction of $(B_i, i\\geq 1)$.\nFinally, when the offspring distributions are lineal fractional, we show that\nthe variables $(A_i, i\\geq 1)$ are independent and identically distributed.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 14 Feb 2022 23:11:59 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-02-16"}
